Conformance

An implementation may be considered compatible when it preserves the observable structural behavior of the reference implementation.

Compatibility may include preservation of:

structural reasoning

evidence generation

evidence integrity behavior

certificate generation

replay validation

deterministic behavior under equivalent visible structure

structural conformance behavior

behavioral specification behavior

controlled mutation-detection behavior

bounded expression-environment behavior

fail-closed rejection of browser-global and undeclared expression dependencies

stable rejection state and certificate under unrelated browser-environment changes

federation behavior

realization verification

application audit behavior

Conformance is evaluated through observable behavior rather than implementation details.

Deterministic behavior refers to observable structural outcomes under equivalent visible inputs.

Implementations are not required to preserve internal implementation details.

However, implementations claiming compatibility should preserve core observable invariants including:

same structure -> same evidence

same structure -> same certificate

same structure -> same replayable outcome

environment-dependent expression -> ABSTAIN

same rejected expression + changed browser environment -> same rejection state + same certificate

and applicable evidence-integrity, realization, federation, and application-level certification guarantees.

Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

SAIL is part of the broader Shunyaya ecosystem of structural and dependency-elimination research.

The reference implementation may be used independently of other Shunyaya projects.

